---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Hobbies">

  <section class="relative bg-gray-950 border-b border-gray-800 overflow-hidden">
    <img
      src="/images/blueprint-hero-bg.png"
      alt=""
      class="absolute inset-0 w-full h-full object-cover object-left opacity-40"
    />
    <div class="relative max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-24 text-center">
      <p class="text-blue-400 text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.2em] uppercase mb-8">
        Personal
      </p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold leading-[1.15] tracking-tight mb-8 text-white">
        Hobbies &amp; Interests
      </h1>
      <p class="text-gray-400 text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed max-w-xl mx-auto">
        What I do when I'm not in front of a screen.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 py-16">

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-5">

      <div class="border border-gray-700 bg-gray-800 rounded-xl p-8">
        <svg class="w-5 h-5 mb-5 text-gray-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 18.75a6 6 0 0 0 6-6v-1.5m-6 7.5a6 6 0 0 1-6-6v-1.5m6 7.5v3.75m-3.75 0h7.5M12 15.75a3 3 0 0 1-3-3V4.5a3 3 0 1 1 6 0v8.25a3 3 0 0 1-3 3Z" /></svg>
        <h2 class="text-base font-bold mb-3 text-white">Gardening</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
          Agronomy is where the academic path started, and it was never really about plants.
          It was about data and maps before either of those words meant what they mean now.
          Soils are archives. Every horizon layer is a record of what happened above it, how long
          ago, under what conditions. A soil survey is a spatial dataset. A nutrient management
          plan is a data model. Crop rotation is a multi-year optimization strategy with inputs,
          outputs, and feedback loops that take seasons to close.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
          The garden is where history, data, and maps intersect at human scale. What grew here
          before matters. What is in the soil matters. What the drainage pattern does in a heavy
          rain matters. None of it is visible on the surface, and all of it is knowable if you
          pay attention to the right signals and remember what the last few years told you.
          That is the same cognitive posture that makes someone good at GIS, or data pipelines,
          or running analytical notebooks against 700 federal construction projects.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          The degree in Agronomy and Environmental Science was the first data science degree
          I ever earned. It just did not have that name yet.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-gray-700 bg-gray-800 rounded-xl p-8">
        <svg class="w-5 h-5 mb-5 text-gray-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M11.42 15.17 17.25 21A2.652 2.652 0 0 0 21 17.25l-5.877-5.877M11.42 15.17l2.496-3.03c.317-.384.74-.626 1.208-.766M11.42 15.17l-4.655 5.653a2.548 2.548 0 1 1-3.586-3.586l6.837-5.63m5.108-.233c.55-.164 1.163-.188 1.743-.14a4.5 4.5 0 0 0 4.486-6.336l-3.276 3.277a3.004 3.004 0 0 1-2.25-2.25l3.276-3.276a4.5 4.5 0 0 0-6.336 4.486c.091 1.076-.071 2.264-.904 2.95l-.102.085m-1.745 1.437L5.909 7.5H4.5L2.25 3.75l1.5-1.5L7.5 4.5v1.409l4.26 4.26m-1.745 1.437 1.745-1.437m6.615 8.206L15.75 15.75M4.867 19.125h.008v.008h-.008v-.008Z" /></svg>
        <h2 class="text-base font-bold mb-3 text-white">Woodworking</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
          The part that nobody talks about is the templates and jigs. Before the real work starts,
          a craftsman builds the constraint. A jig is a physical structure that makes the right cut
          easy and the wrong cut impossible. You spend an hour building it so you never have to
          think about that problem again. Every subsequent piece benefits from that hour forever.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
          That is identical to what a good Python function does. Or a well-designed AI agent. Or
          a data pipeline with validation at the point of entry. The investment is in the structure
          that enforces correctness, not in the heroic effort of getting it right by hand each time.
          The jig removes human judgment from the part where human judgment introduces error,
          and returns it to the part where human judgment is actually the point.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Most people in the shop go straight to the wood. The craftsman goes to the jig first.
          Most people in the codebase go straight to the feature. The engineer goes to the
          constraint first. It is the same discipline, expressed in different materials.
          The garage taught me that before the IDE did.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-dashed border-gray-700 rounded-xl p-8 md:col-span-2 flex items-center justify-center">
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm italic">More coming soon.</p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
